ducation system of Washington.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonlearns.wa.gov/steering.htm|title=Washington Learn Steering Committee|accessdate=23 November 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101103132130/http://www.washingtonlearns.wa.gov/steering.htm|archivedate=3 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\nDennis L. Heck, ''Challenges and Opportunities: The Transformation of Washington's Schools'', Advance Washington (1987)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://dennyheck.house.gov/ Congressman Denny Heck] official U.S. House site\n*[http://www.dennyheckforcongress.com/ Denny Heck for Congress]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Washington/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Denny_Heck_%5BD-10%5D}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=H001064 | votesmart=126058 | fec=H0WA03161 | congress=denny-heck/2170 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n|state    = Washington\n|district = 10\n|before   = Constituency established\n|years    = 2013\u2013present}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tulsi Gabbard]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=204th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[George Holding]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{WA-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heck, Dennis}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Washington House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Political chiefs of staff]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Vancouver, Washington]]\n[[Category:The Evergreen State College alumni]]\n[[Category:Washington (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from Vancouver, Washington]]\n", "name_user": "Schazjmd", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denny_Heck"}
{"title_page": "Secession in China", "text_new": "[[File:Qing Empire circa 1820 EN.svg|thumb|Inner Mongolia and [[Outer Mongolia]] within the Qing dynasty, c. 1820]]\n[[File:Chine 1923-1924.png|thumb|[[Warlord Era]] of China, 1924]]\n\n'''Secession in China''' refers to several secessionist movements in [[Greater China]], which includes the following states and territories:\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of China.svg}} '''[[China|People's Republic of China]] (China or PRC)''' \u2014 China is a [[List of countries and dependencies by area|geographically very large]] (area comparable to the [[United States]]) and [[List of countries and dependencies by population|immensely populous]] (population comparable to [[India]]) country that is [[Administrative divisions of China|subdivided]] into 22 [[Provinces of China|provinces]], 5 [[Autonomous regions of China|autonomous regions]], 4 [[Direct-administered municipalities of China|direct-administered municipalities]], and [[Taiwan Province, People's Republic of China|1 claimed province (Taiwan)]]. The People\u2019s Republic of China additionally claims [[Taiwan, China|Taiwan]], which remains governed by the [[Republic of China]] and has never been controlled by the PRC.\n*{{flagicon image|Flag of Hong Kong.svg}} '''[[Hong Kong|Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China]] (Hong Kong SAR)''' \u2014 Hong Kong is a semi-independent city in [[South China]] that ultimately falls under the sovereignty of the PRC.\n*{{flagicon image|Flag of Macau.svg}} '''[[Macau|Macao (Macau) Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China]] (Macau/Macao SAR)''' \u2014 Macau is a semi-independent city in South China that ultimately falls under the sovereignty of the PRC.\n*{{flagicon image|Flag of Taiwan.svg}} '''[[Taiwan|Republic of China]] (Taiwan or ROC)''' \u2014 Taiwan is an [[Island country|island state]] with [[Foreign relations of Taiwan|very limited official recognition of its sovereignty]] that is located to the southeast of China in the [[Pacific Ocean]], geographically separated from China by the approximately 180-kilometer-wide [[Taiwan Strait]]. Compared to China, Taiwan is approximately 265 times smaller by area (area comparable to [[Bhutan]]) and approximately 58 times less populous (population comparable to [[North Korea]]). The [[Constitution of the Republic of China|constitution of the ROC]] includes territorial claims to most of China, [[Mongolia]], and other relatively minor territories that are administered by other countries. However, the [[Government of the Republic of China|government of Taiwan (ROC)]] doesn't act on the majority of these territorial claims. The [[political status of Taiwan]] is highly ambiguous and controversial. [[Diplomacy|Diplomatic relations]] between China and Taiwan are formally known as [[Cross-Strait relations]] since neither country officially recognizes the other.\n\nThe most significant secessionist movement in China is the [[Taiwan independence movement]]. The movement is complicated by the fact that the Republic of China, which administers the territory known as \"[[Geography of Taiwan|Taiwan]]\" and [[Fujian Province, Republic of China|a few minor islands]] located in \"[[mainland China]]\", is currently engaged in a sovereignty dispute with the People's Republic of China over which government is the legitimate government of \"[[Greater China|all of China]]\", which is said to include both mainland China and Taiwan.\n\nThe second most significant secessionist movement in China is the [[Tibetan independence movement|Tibet independence movement]], which has historically received widespread attention across the [[Western world]] following the [[incorporation of Tibet into the People's Republic of China]]. China (PRC) currently administers the [[Tibet|historical region of Tibet]] as two main subdivisions, which are [[Qinghai|Qinghai Province]] and the [[Tibet Autonomous Region|Xizang (Tibet) Autonomous Region]].\n\nThe third most significant secessionist movement in China is the [[Uyghur nationalism|East Turkestan independence movement]], which has recently come to the attention of foreign media following accusations that China (PRC) has established \"[[Xinjiang re-education camps|re-education camps]]\" in the [[Xinjiang|Xinjiang Autonomous Region]], which are holding hundreds of thousands or even up to a million [[Islam in China|Muslims]] (especially [[Uyghurs|ethnic Uyghurs]]) without trial.\n\nThe fourth most significant secessionist movement in China is the [[Inner Mongolian independence movement|South Mongolia independence movement]], which primarily aims to achieve independence for the Chinese (PRC) [[Inner Mongolia|Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region]] as \"South Mongolia\" and which secondarily aims to incorporate South Mongolia into the currently existing sovereign state known as \"[[Mongolia]]\". This movement has much lower [[grassroots]] support compared to the other major secessionist movements in China.\n\nAdditionally, the regions of [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macau]], which are both administered as \"[[Special administrative regions of China|Special Administrative Regions]]\" of China (PRC), are hosts to their own independence movements. Currently, the two regions are already highly autonomous, but they are gradually being encroached on by China (PRC), and their autonomy officially ends in 2047 and 2049 respectively. The [[Hong Kong independence|independence movement in Hong Kong]] is stronger than the one in Macau.\n\nFurthermore, there are other minor secessionist movements in China, such as the [[Manchurian nationalism|Manchuria independence movement]], [[Shanghai]] independence movement, Cantonia ([[Guangdong]]) independence movement, etc. However, these movements are somewhat negligible compared to the aforementioned movements.\n\n==List of secessionist movements in People's Republic of China==\n==== Notes ====\n\n* {{flagdeco|Taiwan}} [[Taiwan]] is not included in this list because it has never been governed by the [[People's Republic of China]].\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:100%\"\n|-\n! width=\"175\" |Claimed Territory\n! width=\"200\" |Currently Under\n! width=\"100\" |Capital City\n! width=\"100\" |Area\n! width=\"100\" |Population\n! width=\"125\" |Ethnic Group\n! width=\"175\" |Primary Independence Movement\n|-\n|'''{{flagdeco|East Turkestan}} [[East Turkestan]]''' ||[[Xinjiang]]\n||[[\u00dcr\u00fcmqi]]|| align=\"center\" |1,700,000 || align=\"center\" |20,000,000 ||[[Uyghurs|Uyghur people]]||[[East Turkestan independence movement]]\n|-\n|'''Eastern Mongolia''' ||[[Inner Mongolia]]<br>\n* [[Hulunbuir]]\n|[[Hailar District|Hailar]]\n| align=\"center\" |263,953 || align=\"center\" |2,500,000 ||[[Daur people]]||Eastern Mongolia independence movement\n|-\n|'''[[File:Flag of the Zhuang people.svg|23px|border]] Gvangjsih''' ||[[Guangxi]]\n|[[Nanning]] (Namzningz)\n| align=\"center\" |236,700 || align=\"center\" |50,000,000 ||[[Zhuang people]]||Zhuang independence movement\n|-\n|'''{{flagdeco|Hong Kong}} Hong Kong'''||[[Hong Kong]]\n||[[Hong Kong]]|| align=\"center\" |1,110 || align=\"center\" |7,500,000 ||[[Hongkongers|Hong Kong people]]||[[Hong Kong independence|Hong Kong independence movement]]\n|-\n|'''[[File:Flag of the Inner Mongolian People's Party.svg|23px|border]] Inner Mongolia'''||[[Inner Mongolia]]\n||[[Hohhot]]|| align=\"center\" |1,183,000 || align=\"center\" |25,000,000 ||[[Mongols in China|Chinese Mongols]]||[[Inner Mongolian independence movement]]\n|-\n|'''[[File:Lahu flag.svg|23px|border]] Lahu Republic''' ||[[Yunnan]]<br>\n* [[Lancang Lahu Autonomous County]]\n|[[Pu'er City|Pu'er]]\n| align=\"center\" |8,807 || align=\"center\" |8,000,000 ||[[Lahu people]]||Lahu independence movement\n|-\n|'''{{flagdeco|Macau}} Macau''' ||[[Macau]]\n||[[Macau]]|| align=\"center\" |115 || align=\"center\" |700,000 ||[[Macau people]]||[[Macau independence|Macau independence movement]]\n|-\n|'''[[File:Ma 