st the [[Chinese Civil War]] against the [[Communist Party of China|Chinese Communist Party]] and was forced to flee from its own borders and into Japanese Formosa. The Republic of China had recently occupied and annexed Japanese Formosa four years earlier, in 1945. This left a unique situation wherein the [[Rump state|rump-state]] of the Republic of China was, essentially, overlapping with the remnants of a now-defunct Japanese Formosa. Note that this was not a perfect overlap since the Republic of China still managed to hold onto a few small pieces of China, namely Kinmen (including [[Wuqiu, Kinmen|Wuqiu]]) and Matsu.\n\nIn modern times, the [[political status of Taiwan]] has developed into, perhaps, one of the most unique geopolitical anomalies currently in existence worldwide. The [[Revolution|revolutionary]] forces that drove the [[Republic of China on Taiwan|Republic of China out of China and into Taiwan]] established a new Chinese regime shortly before this occurred, and named it the \"[[China|People's Republic of China]]\". This regime not only lays claim to all of the Republic of China's previously-held territory in China but also the Republic of China's newly-acquired territory in Taiwan. To this day, the People's Republic of China is still laying claim to Taiwan, and the Republic of China still controls Taiwan.\n\n=== Ethnic groups of Taiwan (ROC) ===\n{{Main|Taiwanese people|Han Taiwanese|Taiwanese indigenous peoples}}\n[[Image:Map of Taiwan.jpg|thumb|right|Topography of Taiwan]]\n\nOfficially, Taiwan (ROC) is home to two main native ethnic groups, the [[Han Chinese]] (aka \"[[Han Taiwanese]]\") and the [[Taiwanese indigenous peoples]] (who are ethnically [[Austronesian peoples|Austronesian]]). Additionally, these two main native ethnic groups can be classified into several subdivisions. Regarding the Han Chinese, they can be divided into the [[Hoklo Taiwanese|Taiwanese Hoklo people]], the [[Taiwanese Hakka|Taiwanese Hakka people]], and the somewhat outdated term \"[[Mainland Chinese]] in Taiwan (ROC)\" (which refers to Mainland Chinese people who migrated to the territory of Taiwan during the late-1940s and early-1950s). Regarding the Taiwanese indigenous peoples, there are currently sixteen officially recognized tribes, and perhaps several more which are officially unrecognized. \n\nThe Taiwanese Hoklo and Taiwanese Hakka peoples, as well as, occasionally, the Taiwanese indigenous peoples, are often collectively referred to as \"Taiwanese Benshengren\" by the peoples of Taiwan (ROC), which roughly translates to \"Original Province Person(s)\". Meanwhile, the Mainland Chinese in Taiwan (ROC) (not to be confused with [[Chinese people|PRC citizens]] in Taiwan), who originate from various provinces of China, are often referred to as \"Taiwanese Waishengren\" by the peoples of Taiwan (ROC), which roughly translates to \"Outside Province Person(s)\".\n\nThese are the respective proportionate populations of these ethnic groups in Taiwan (ROC).\n\n* Taiwanese Benshengren people make up around 86% of the native population of Taiwan (ROC).\n** Taiwanese Hoklo people make up around 70% of the native population of Taiwan (ROC).\n** Taiwanese Hakka people make up around 14% of the native population of Taiwan (ROC).\n** Taiwanese indigenous peoples make up around 2% of the native population of Taiwan (ROC).\n* Taiwanese Waishengren people make up around 14% of the native population of Taiwan (ROC).\n\n==== The peoples of Kinmen (Quemoy) and Matsu (Lienchiang) ====\n{{See also|Taiwan independence movement#The issue of Kinmen (Quemoy) and Matsu (Lienchiang)}}\nFurthermore, the peoples of Kinmen and Matsu may identify themselves as \"Kinmenese\" and \"Matsunese\", respectively. The Kinmenese and Matsunese peoples are mostly Hoklo (Han) people, but whether they identify as \"Taiwanese\" is inconsistent throughout their populations. Historically, Kinmen and Matsu were parts of [[Fujian|Fujian Province, China]], and were never parts of Japanese Formosa or other historical Taiwanese regimes. However, Kinmen and Matsu have been administered by Taiwan (ROC) ever since 1949 (and by the ROC since it ruled mainland China). As such, although Kinmen and Matsu are not technically parts of the territory of Taiwan, many people living in these territories or originating from them view themselves as \"Taiwanese\", in a variety of contexts. Conversely, many people living in these territories still identify as Mainland Chinese, distinct from \"Mainland Chinese in Taiwan (ROC)\" or \"Taiwanese Waishengren\".\n\n==== Ethnic groups of Taiwan Province, PRC ====\n{{See also|Taiwan Province, People's Republic of China}}\nChina (PRC) claims [[Geography of Taiwan|Taiwan]] and [[Penghu]] as its own province and hence has its own ethnic classifications for the native ethnic groups. However, most countries disregard these ethnic classifications in favour of the local ethnic classifications defined by Taiwan (ROC).\n\nAccording to China (PRC), Taiwan is divided into the Han Chinese and the Gaoshanren. \"Gaoshanren\" means \"High mountain person(s)\" and refers to the various Taiwanese indigenous peoples as a single ethnic group.\n\n=== Primary forces supporting Taiwan independence ===\n{{Main|Taiwan independence movement|Pan-Green Coalition}}\n\n==== Pan-Green Coalition support for Taiwan independence ====\n[[Taiwan independence movement|Taiwan independence]] is a complex movement with many different parties being involved. The party which is most commonly associated with the movement is the [[Pan-Green Coalition]], a collective of several [[Political party|political parties]] which advocate for the independence of a [[Multiculturalism|multicultural]] [[sovereign state]] on Taiwan and [[Penghu]] (and sometimes also the ROC-controlled territories of [[Kinmen]] and [[Matsu Islands|Matsu]]) by the name of the \"Republic of Taiwan\". [[File:Flag of World Taiwanese Congress.svg|22px|border]] [[File:Flag of Taiwan proposed 1996.svg|22px|border]] [[File:908\u53f0\u7063\u570b\u904b\u52d5.svg|22px|border]] This movement is the most well-known one internationally since the most senior political party in the Pan-Green Coalition, the [[Democratic Progressive Party]], has risen to power in Taiwan (ROC) twice within the past two decades. Notably, this has been achieved by [[Democracy|democratic]] [[Election|elections]], rather than by [[Coup d'\u00e9tat|military coup]]. This indicates that there is widespread support (or, at the very least, complacency) in Taiwan (ROC) regarding the Taiwan independence movement (as defined by the Pan-Green Coalition).\n\nOther major political parties associated with the Pan-Green Coalition include the [[New Power Party]] and the [[Taiwan Solidarity Union]]. Additionally the organization [[World United Formosans for Independence]] is an ally of the Pan-Green Coalition.\n\n==== Indigenous independence movements ====\n\nWhile many [[Taiwanese aborigines|Taiwanese indigenous people(s)]] support the Pan-Green Coalition, many also support the [[Taiwan First Nations Party]], a political party in Taiwan (ROC) which specifically advocates for the autonomy or possible independence of the Taiwan indigenous peoples. The [[Council of Indigenous Peoples]] is also closely affiliated with the movement advocating for Taiwanese indigenous autonomy or independence. An autonomous or independent Taiwanese indigenous state might be named \"[[Taiwanese indigenous peoples#Aboriginal political movement|Aborigines of Taiwan's Autonomy]]\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.culturalsurvival.org/publications/cultural-survival-quarterly/first-nations-taiwan-special-report-taiwans-indigenous|title=The First Nations of Taiwan: A Special Report on Taiwan's indigenous peoples|website=www.culturalsurvival.org|language=en|access-date=2019-01-30}}</ref>.\n\n=== Primary forces opposed to Taiwan independence ===\n{{Main|One-China policy|Anti-Secession Law|1992 Consensus}}\nThe relationship of China with Taiwan is confusing and convoluted. Simply put, Taiwan (ROC) is an independent country which is competing with China (PRC) for recognition as the sole legitimate government of China, and within Taiwan (ROC) there is a nationwide secessionist movement which has garnered the support of roughly half the country. The secessionist movement in Taiwan (ROC) is equally aimed at both the Taiwan (ROC) government itself as well as the China (PRC) government which is claiming the entirety of Taiwan (ROC) as its own territory.\n\nChina (PRC) is widely recognized as the legitimate government of both China and Taiwan. This means that the Taiwan (ROC) country is not only fighting against Taiwanese secessionists, but also against China (PRC) simultaneously. Compared to China (PRC), Taiwan (ROC) is at a severe disadvantage but isn't completely powerless, since most of the world isn't too supportive of the possible dissolving of the Taiwan (ROC) country. However, the sovereignty of Taiwan (ROC) is being critically threatened by the Taiwan independence movement, which essentially aims to overthrow Taiwan (ROC).\n\n==== China (PRC) opposition to Taiwan independence ====\n{{Main|Taiwan, China}}\nChina (PRC) considers Taiwan area, which is currently administered by Taiwan (ROC), as part of its own territory, and forces other countries to abide by a \"[[One-China policy]]\" as a prerequisite for establishing official diplomatic relations with China (PRC). The One-China policy is aimed at both the rival Chinese government known as the \"Republic of China\", as well as the localist Taiwan independence movement. In 2005, China (PRC) passed the \"[[Anti-Secession Law]]\" in an attempt to suppress the Taiwan independence movement.\n\n==== Pan-Blue Coalition opposition to Taiwan independence ====\n{{Main|Pan-Blue Coalition}}\nThe [[Pan-Blue Coalition]] of Taiwan (ROC) is an alliance of political parties which are loyal to the ROC, currently restricted to the territory of Taiwan and some minor islands of Fujian Province. The Pan-Blue Coalition asserts that the ROC is the sole legitimate government of all of China, which consists of \"both mainland China and Taiwan\", and that the ROC has never for a single day lost its sovereignty. The Pan-Blue Coalition is opposed to Taiwan independence but is also opposed to a PRC takeover of Taiwan.\n\n== China (PRC) (aka \"mainland China\") ==\n[[File:China autonomous regions numbered.svg|thumb]]\n\n\n{{further|Autonomous administrative divisions of China|Special administrative regions of China|One country, Two systems||}}\n\nThe [[People's Republic of China|People's Republic of China (China/PRC)]] considers itself to be the sole legitimate government of \"both mainland China area and Taiwan area\".\n\nThe territory controlled by the PRC consists of [[mainland China]], [[Hong Kong]], and [[Macau]]. The PRC also claims all [[Taiwan|ROC]]-controlled territories as part of its own territory. The PRC has established \"[[Special administrative regions of China|Special Administrative Regions]]\" (SARs) in [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macau]] under the [[one country, two systems|One Country Two Systems]] policy. \n\n=== Tibet region (Qinghai, Xizang, etc) ===\n{{Main|Tibetan independence movement}}\n\nThe [[Tibetan people|Tibetans]] are an ethnic group in Tibet that is distinct from the [[Han Chinese]]. Their proposed state is Tibet. {{flagicon|Tibet}} Supporters of Tibetan independence believe that Tibet is a distinct country which is being occupied by China (PRC). The [[Tibet|Tibet region]] was independent before the [[Mongols]] invaded the Tibet region and incorporated it into the [[Mongol Empire]]. After this, Tibet became part of the [[Yuan dynasty]] (of China), then the [[Qing dynasty]] (of China), then experienced a few decades of ''de facto'' independence before it was incorporated into China (PRC). \n\nAfter the failed Tibetan uprising, some Tibetans followed the Dalai Lama into India, establishing a government-in-exile called the [[Central Tibetan Administration]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dalailama.com/page.99.htm|title=Speech of His Holiness the Dalai Lama to the European Parliament, Strasbourg|date=14 October 2001|publisher=The Office of His Holiness the Dalai Lama|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325221348/http://www.dalailama.com/page.99.htm|archivedate=25 March 2009|url-status=dead|accessdate=11 April 2009}}</ref>, a member of the [[Unrepresented Nations and Peoples Organization]], in Dharmashala, Himachal Pradesh, India. The major political parties in Tibet are the [[International Tibet Independence Movement]] and the [[National Democratic Party of Tibet]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rangzen.org/|title=INTERNATIONAL TIBET INDEPENDENCE MOVEMENT|publisher=International Tibet Independence Movement|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416141657/http://www.rangzen.org/|archive-date=16 April 2009|url-status=live|accessdate=11 April 2009}}</ref>. Their advocacy groups include the [[Students for a Free Tibet]], the [[Tibetan Youth Congress]], and the [[International Campaign for Tibet]].\n\n=== Xinjiang Autonomous Region ===\n{{Main|Uyghur independence}}\nXinjiang is home to several ethnic groups, including the [[Uyghurs]], the [[Kazakhs in China|Kazakhs]], the [[Tajiks of Xinjiang|Tajiks]], as well as the [[Han Chinese]]. \n\nThe ethnic Uyghur people view themselves as [[Indigenous peoples|indigenous]] to Xinjiang, but the government of China (PRC) opposes this notion. Whether they are indigenous is very significant, because it defines whether Xinjiang \"belongs\" to the Uyghurs or to China (PRC). China (PRC) has been in the process of encouraging Han Chinese settlement in Xinjiang for several decades, which is a source of concern for the Uyghur secessionists of Xinjiang.\n\nThe Uyghur secessionists propose independence for Xinjiang as [[East Turkestan]]. [[File:Kokbayraq flag.svg|22px|border]] The borders of the proposed state will roughly match the borders of the Chinese autonomous region which currently occupies the territory. Uyghur secessionists have set up a government-in-exile called the [[East Turkistan Government in Exile|East Turkestan Government in Exile]]. \n\nThe main advocacy group of Uyghur independence is the [[World Uyghur Congress]], a member of the [[Unrepresented Nations and Peoples Organization]].\n\n==== Conflict in Xinjiang ====\n{{Main|Xinjiang conflict|Xinjiang re-education camps}}\nSeveral armed insurgency groups are fighting the Chinese (PRC) government in Xinjiang, namely the [[Turkistan Islamic Party|Turkestan Islamic Party]] and the [[East Turkestan Liberation Organization]], which some people consider to be associated with [[Al Qaeda|Al-Qaeda]] and the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thediplomat.com/2017/03/al-qaeda-and-islamic-state-take-aim-at-china/|title=Al-Qaeda and Islamic State Take Aim at China. Why have both groups turned their attention to Beijing?|website=The Diplomat|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314072328/http://thediplomat.com/2017/03/al-qaeda-and-islamic-state-take-aim-at-china/|archive-date=14 March 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref>.\n\nIn response, China (PRC) has established so-called \"re-education camps\" in Xinjiang, allegedly as a measure to deal with this violent insurgency, which China (PRC) has labelled as \"terrorism\".\n\nThese re-education camps have become a huge source of controversy in the [[Western world|West]], due to concerns that they are imprisoning ethnic Uyghurs and other [[Islam in China|native Muslims]] ''en masse'' without trial.\n\nChina (PRC) claims that the World Uyghur Congress is formally associated with terrorist groups in Xinjiang, but this has yet to be proven.\n\n=== Inner Mongolia ===\n{{Main|Inner Mongolian independence movement}}\n\nThe region of [[Inner Mongolia]] is home to several ethnic groups, namely the Han Chinese and [[Mongolian people|Mongolians]].\n\nSome Mongolians in Inner Mongolia advocate for the independence of Inner Mongolia as a new country named [[Inner Mongolian People's Party|Republic of South Mongolia]] [[File:Flag of the Inner Mongolian People's Party.svg|22px|border]] or unification with [[Mongolia|Mongolia.]] {{flagicon|Mongolia}} \n\nSouth Mongolian independence is supported by these political parties: the [[Inner Mongolian People's Party]], a member of the [[Unrepresented Nations and Peoples Organization]]; the [[Southern Mongolian Democratic Alliance]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smhric.org/news_39.htm|title=\"Inner Mongolian People's Party\" and the basic facts about its key members|publisher=Southern Mongolian Human Rights Information Center|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225210314/http://www.smhric.org/news_39.htm|archive-date=25 February 2009|url-status=live|accessdate=11 April 2009}}</ref>; and the [[Mongolian Liberal Union Party]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lupm.org/japanese/index.htm|title=\u30e2\u30f3\u30b4\u30eb\u81ea\u7531\u9023\u76df\u515a|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100726004625/http://www.lupm.org/japanese/index.htm|archive-date=26 July 2010|url-status=live|accessdate=22 November 2010}}(JP)</ref>.\n\n==Special Administrative Regions of China==\n[[Image:China Hong Kong location map.svg|frameless|right]]\n=== Hong Kong ===\n{{Main|Hong Kong}}\n\n==== Background ====\n{{Main|History of Hong Kong}}\n'''[[Hong Kong]]''' is a highly [[Autonomous administrative division|autonomous]] [[city]] that is under Chinese sovereignty but operates as an independent country in many respects and is somewhat comparable to a [[Dependent territory|dependency]]. Officially, Hong Kong is considered to be a [[Special administrative regions of China|'''Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China''']]. Geographically, Hong Kong is attached to [[mainland China]] via [[Guangdong|Guangdong Province]] in the [[South China|south]] but lies mostly on a small [[peninsula]], of which [[Kowloon Peninsula]] is a part, as well as many small islands nearby to the peninsula, the most notable of which is [[Hong Kong Island]].\n\nHistorically, Hong Kong Island was ceded by the [[Qing dynasty]] to the [[British Empire]] in 1842 following the British victory in the [[First Opium War]] and was promptly developed into a [[Crown colony|British colony]]. The nearby Kowloon Peninsula was ceded in 1860 following the British victory in the [[Second Opium War]] and was incorporated into Hong Kong. Finally, the last major territorial acquisition was the nearby [[New Territories]], leased by the British for 99 years in 1898 by means of the [[Convention for the Extension of Hong Kong Territory]]; this territorial change was made in the aftermath of the [[First Sino-Japanese War]], which Hong Kong was not directly involved in.\n\nIn 1997, the [[China|People's Republic of China]] and the [[United Kingdom|United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland]] signed the [[Sino-British Joint Declaration]] in order to [[Handover of Hong Kong|transfer Hong Kong]] from the United Kingdom to China. China agreed to govern Hong Kong under a so-called \"[[One country, two systems|One Country Two Systems]]\" framework, which would grant Hong Kong a high degree of autonomy whilst simultaneously granting China sovereignty over Hong Kong.\n\n==== Culture ====\n{{Main|Culture of Hong Kong}}\nThe three main regions of Hong Kong, consisting of Hong Kong Island, Kowloon Peninsula, and the New Territories, were all under British rule for different lengths of time, ranging from 99 to 155 years. Due to this lengthy period of British rule, Hong Kong's infrastructure, society, and culture became broadly British. Hong Kong also developed a distinct culture from mainland China because many [[Mainland Chinese]] immigrated to Hong Kong, often illegally, in order to escape persecution by the [[Communist Party of China]] or to seek better living standards. Most of the Mainland Chinese immigrants to Hong Kong were [[Cantonese people]], though there were also significant numbers of [[Hoklo people|Hoklo]], [[Teochew people|Teochew]], [[Hakka people|Hakka]], and [[Shanghainese people|Shanghainese]] immigrants. In the present day, the vast majority of Hong Kong people can trace their ancestry, whether fully or partially, to these Cantonese immigrants or others who came to Hong Kong throughout the 20th century. Native Hong Kong people, that is, people who were living in Hong Kong prior to British rule, constitute a minority of the population. Hong Kong also hosts minority populations of [[South Asian ethnic groups|South Asians]], [[Ethnic groups of Southeast Asia|Southeast Asians]], [[Ethnic groups in Europe|Europeans]], [[North America|North Americans]], and other broad ethnic groups.\n\n==== Independence movement ====\n{{main|Hong Kong independence}}The Hong Kong independence movement advocates for the full independence of Hong Kong as a \"[[city-state]]\", similar to [[Singapore]]. Related sovereign movements in Hong Kong include the movement to maintain Hong Kong's status as a \"Special Administrative Region\" indefinitely, the movement to return Hong Kong to [[British Hong Kong|British rule]], the movement to admit Hong Kong into the [[United States|United States of America]], and the movement to admit Hong Kong into the [[Taiwan|Republic of China (Taiwan)]].\n\n=== Macau ===\n{{Empty section|date=January 2020}}\n\n==Related pages==\n* [[Demographics of China#Population density and distribution|Demographics of China]]\n* [[Template:Han Chinese subgroups]]\n* [[Ethnic minorities in China]]\n* [[Ethnic issues in China]]\n* [[Ethnic groups in Chinese history]]\n* [[Languages of China]]\n* [[Language Atlas of China]]\n* [[Standard Chinese]]\n* [[Autonomous administrative divisions of China]]\n* [[Administrative divisions of China]]\n* [[Autonomous regions of China]]\n* [[Anti-Secession Law]]\n* [[Xinjiang conflict]]\n* [[List of active separatist movements in Asia]]\n* [[Political status of Taiwan]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Other websites==\n* {{YouTube|C4W5Rhg9wIk|China must stop the genocide in East Turkestan Special News Daily Voice News}}\n\n{{Secession in Countries}}\n\n[[Category:National liberation movements]]\n[[Category:Politics of China]]\n[[Category:Separatism in China]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Qing Empire circa 1820 EN.svg|thumb|Inner Mongolia and [[Outer Mongolia]] within the Qing dynasty, c. 1820]]\n[[File:Chine 1923-1924.png|thumb|[[Warlord Era]] of China, 1924]]\n\n'''Secession in China''' refers to several secessionist movements in [[Greater China]], which includes the following states and territories:\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of China.svg}} '''[[China|People's Republic of China]] (China or PRC)''' \u2014 China is a [[List of countries and dependencies by area|geographically very large]] (area comparable to the [[United States]]) and [[List of countries and dependencies by population|immensely populous]] (population comparable to [[India]]) country that is [[Administrative divisions of China|subdivided]] into 22 [[Provinces of China|provinces]], 5 [[Autonomous regions of China|autonomous regions]], 4 [[Direct-administered municipalities of China|direct-administered municipalities]], and [[Taiwan Province, People's Republic of China|1 claimed province (Taiwan)]]. The People\u2019s Republic of China additionally claims [[Taiwan, China|Taiwan]], which remains governed by the [[Republic of China]] and has never been controlled by the PRC.\n*{{flagicon image|Flag of Hong Kong.svg}} '''[[Hong Kong|Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China]] (Hong Kong SAR)''' \u2014 Hong Kong is a semi-independent city in [[South China]] that ultimately falls under the sovereignty of the PRC.\n*{{flagicon image|Flag of Macau.svg}} '''[[Macau|Macao (Macau) Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China]] (Macau/Macao SAR)''' \u2014 Macau is a semi-independent city in South China that ultimately falls under the sovereignty of the PRC.\n*{{flagicon image|Flag of Taiwan.svg}} '''[[Taiwan|Republic of China]] (Taiwan or ROC)''' \u2014 Taiwan is an [[Island country|island state]] with [[Foreign relations of Taiwan|very limited official recognition of its sovereignty]] that is located to the southeast of China in the [[Pacific Ocean]], geographically separated from China by the approximately 180-kilometer-wide [[Taiwan Strait]]. Compared to China, Taiwan is approximately 265 times smaller by area (area comparable to [[Bhutan]]) and approximately 58 times less populous (population comparable to [[North Korea]]). The [[Constitution of the Republic of China|constitution of the ROC]] includes territorial claims to most of China, [[Mongolia]], and other relatively minor territories that are administered by other countries. However, the [[Government of the Republic of China|government of Taiwan (ROC)]] doesn't act on the majority of these territorial claims. The [[political status of Taiwan]] is highly ambiguous and controversial. [[Diplomacy|Diplomatic relations]] between China and Taiwan are formally known as [[Cross-Strait relations]] since neither country officially recognizes the other.\n\nThe most significant secessionist movement in China is the [[Taiwan independence movement]]. The movement is complicated by the fact that the Republic of China, which administers the territory known as \"[[Geography of Taiwan|Taiwan]]\" and [[Fujian Province, Republic of China|a few minor islands]] located in \"[[mainland China]]\", is currently engaged in a sovereignty dispute with the People's Republic of China over which government is the legitimate government of \"[[Greater China|all of China]]\", which is said to include both mainland China and Taiwan.\n\nThe second most significant secessionist movement in China is the [[Tibetan independence movement|Tibet independence movement]], which has historically received widespread attention across the [[Western world]] following the [[incorporation of Tibet into the People's Republic of China]]. China (PRC) currently administers the [[Tibet|historical region of Tibet]] as two main subdivisions, which are [[Qinghai|Qinghai Province]] and the [[Tibet Autonomous Region|Xizang (Tibet) Autonomous Region]].\n\nThe third most significant secessionist movement in China is the [[Uyghur nationalism|East Turkestan independence movement]], which has recently come to the attention of foreign media following accusations that China (PRC) has established \"[[Xinjiang re-education camps|re-education camps]]\" in the [[Xinjiang|Xinjiang Autonomous Region]], which are holding hundreds of thousands or even up to a million [[Islam in China|Muslims]] (especially [[Uyghurs|ethnic Uyghurs]]) without trial.\n\nThe fourth most significant secessionist movement in China is the [[Inner Mongolian independence movement|South Mongolia independence movement]], which primarily aims to achieve independence for the Chinese (PRC) [[Inner Mongolia|Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region]] as \"South Mongolia\" and which secondarily aims to incorporate South Mongolia into the currently existing sovereign state known as \"[[Mongolia]]\". This movement has much lower [[grassroots]] support compared to the other major secessionist movements in China.\n\nAdditionally, the regions of [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macau]], which are both administered as \"[[Special administrative regions of China|Special Administrative Regions]]\" of China (PRC), are hosts to their own independence movements. Currently, the two regions are already highly autonomous, but they are gradually being encroached on by China (PRC), and their autonomy officially ends in 2047 and 2049 respectively. The [[Hong Kong independence|independence movement in Hong Kong]] is stronger than the one in Macau.\n\nFurthermore, there are other minor secessionist movements in China, such as the [[Manchurian nationalism|Manchuria independence movement]], [[Shanghai]] independence movement, Cantonia ([[Guangdong]]) independence movement, etc. However, these movements are somewhat negligible compared to the aforementioned movements.\n\n==List of secessionist movements in People's Republic of China==\n==== Notes ====\n\n* {{flagdeco|Taiwan}} [[Taiwan]] is not included in this list because it has never been governed by the [[People's Republic of China]].\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:100%\"\n|-\n! width=\"175\" |Claimed Territory\n! width=\"200\" |Currently Under\n! width=\"100\" |Capital City\n! width=\"100\" |Area\n! width=\"100\" |Population\n! width=\"125\" |Ethnic Group\n! width=\"175\" |Primary Independence Movement\n|-\n|'''[[File:Basurian independence movement .gif|23px|border]] Basu''' ||[[Sichuan]]<br>[[Chongqing]]\n|[[Chengdu]] (Chengtu)\n| align=\"center\" |485,000 || align=\"center\" |81,000,000 ||[[Sichuanese people]]||Sichuan independence movement\n|-\n|'''[[File:Great Cantonia Flag.svg|23px|border]] Canton''' ||[[Guangdong]]\n|[[Guangzhou]] (Kwangchow)\n| align=\"center\" |179,800 || align=\"center\" |113,000,000 ||[[Cantonese people]]||{{ill|Canton independence movement|zh|\u5e7f\u4e1c\u72ec\u7acb\u8fd0\u52a8}}\n|-\n|'''Dongia''' ||[[Guizhou]]<br>\n* [[Liping County]]\n|[[Liping County|Liping]]\n| align=\"center\" |4,439 || align=\"center\" |3,000,000 ||[[Kam people]]||Kam independence movement\n|-\n|'''{{flagdeco|East Turkestan}} [[East Turkestan]]''' ||[[Xinjiang]]\n||[[\u00dcr\u00fcmqi]]|| align=\"center\" |1,700,000 || align=\"center\" |20,000,000 ||[[Uyghurs|Uyghur people]]||[[East Turkestan independence movement]]\n|-\n|'''Eastern Mongolia''' ||[[Inner Mongolia]]<br>\n* [[Hulunbuir]]\n|[[Hailar District|Hailar]]\n| align=\"center\" |263,953 || align=\"center\" |2,500,000 ||[[Daur people]]||Eastern Mongolia independence movement\n|-\n|'''[[File:Flag of the Zhuang people.svg|23px|border]] Gvangjsih''' ||[[Guangxi]]\n|[[Nanning]] (Namzningz)\n| align=\"center\" |236,700 || align=\"center\" |50,000,000 ||[[Zhuang people]]||Zhuang independence movement\n|-\n|'''[[File:Flag of the Republic of Hainan (Proposal).png|23px|border]] Hainam''' ||[[Hainan]]\n|[[Haikou]] (Hoihow)\n| align=\"center\" |35,354 || align=\"center\" |10,000,000 ||[[Hainan people]]||Hainan independence movement\n|-\n|'''Hokkien''' ||[[Fujian]]\n|[[Fuzhou]] (Foochow)\n| align=\"center\" |121,400 || align=\"center\" |38,000,000 ||[[Hoklo people]]||Hokkien independence movement\n|-\n|'''{{flagdeco|Hong Kong}} Hong Kong'''||[[Hong Kong]]\n||[[Hong Kong]]|| align=\"center\" |1,110 || align=\"center\" |7,500,000 ||[[Hongkongers|Hong Kong people]]||[[Hong Kong independence|Hong Kong independence movement]]\n|-\n|'''[[File:Flag of the Inner Mongolian People's Party.svg|23px|border]] Inner Mongolia'''||[[Inner Mongolia]]\n||[[Hohhot]]|| align=\"center\" |1,183,000 || align=\"center\" |25,000,000 ||[[Mongols in China|Chinese Mongols]]||[[Inner Mongolian independence movement]]\n|-\n|'''Kiangsi''' ||[[Jiangxi]]\n|[[Nanchang]] (Nanciong)\n| align=\"center\" |166,919 || align=\"center\" |45,000,000 ||[[Gan Chinese-speaking people|Gan people]]||Gan independence movement\n|-\n|'''[[File:Lahu flag.svg|23px|border]] Lahu Republic''' ||[[Yunnan]]<br>\n* [[Lancang Lahu Autonomous County]]\n|[[Pu'er City|Pu'er]]\n| align=\"center\" |8,807 || align=\"center\" |8,000,000 ||[[Lahu people]]||Lahu independence movement\n|-\n|'''{{flagdeco|Macau}} Macau''' ||[[Macau]]\n||[[Macau]]|| align=\"center\" |115 || align=\"center\" |700,000 ||[[Macau people]]||[[Macau independence|Macau independence movement]]\n|-\n|'''{{flagdeco|Manchukuo}} [[Manchuria]]''' ||[[Heilongjiang]]<br>[[Jiling]]<br>[[Liaoning]]\n|[[Harbin]] (Halbin)\n| align=\"center\" |787,000 || align=\"center\" | 112,000,000 ||[[Manchu people]]||[[Manchukuo Temporary Government]]\n|-\n|'''[[File:Ma clique flag kaiserreich.png|23px|border]] Ninghsia''' ||[[Ningxia]]\n|[[Yinchuan]] (Yinchwan)\n| align=\"center\" |66,400 || align=\"center\" |11,000,000 ||[[Hui people]]||Hui independence movement\n|-\n|'''[[File:Santania flag proposal .jpg|23px|border]] Santania''' ||[[Gansu]]<br>\n* [[Dongxiang Autonomous County]]\n|Tangwangchuan\n| align=\"center\" |8,169 || align=\"center\" |2,000,000 ||[[Dongxiangs|Dongxiang people]]||Dongxiang independence movement\n|-\n|'''[[File:Proposed National Flag of Shanghai.jpg|23px|border]] Shanghai''' ||[[Shanghai]]\n||[[Shanghai]]|| align=\"center\" |6,340 || align=\"center\" |24,000,000 ||[[Shanghainese people]]||Shanghai independence movement\n|-\n|'''Sipsong Panna''' || [[Yunnan]]<br>\n* [[Xishuangbanna Dai Autonomous Prefecture]]\n|[[Jinghong]]\n| align=\"center\" |19,700 || align=\"center\" |1,200,000 ||[[Dai people]]||Dai independence movement\n|-\n|'''Teoshan''' ||[[Guangdong]]<br>\n* [[Chaozhou]]\n* [[Shantou]]\n* [[Jieyang]]\n|[[Chaozhou]] (Teochew)\n| align=\"center\" |10,415 || align=\"center\" |14,000,000 ||[[Teochew people]]||Teoshan independence movement\n|-\n|'''{{flagdeco|Tibet}} [[Tibet]]''' ||[[Tibet Autonomous Region]]<br>[[Qinghai]]\n||[[Lhasa]]|| align=\"center\" |2,500,000 || align=\"center\" |10,000,000 ||[[Tibetan people]]||[[Tibetan independence movement]]\n|-\n|'''[[Wu (region)|Wuyue]]''' ||[[Jiangsu]]<br>\n* [[Suzhou]]\n* [[Wuxi]]\n* [[Changzhou]]\n* [[Nantong]]<br>\n[[Zhejiang]]\n|[[Hangzhou]] (Hangtsei)\n| align=\"center\" |128,000 || align=\"center\" |85,000,000 ||[[Wu Chinese-speaking people|Wuyue people]]||Wuyue independence movement\n|-\n|'''[[File:Xiangese republic .png|23px|border|]] Xiang ||[[Hunan]]\n|[[Changsha]] (Tsaso)\n| align=\"center\" |210,000 || align=\"center\" |67,000,000 ||[[Xiang Chinese|Xiang people]]||{{ill|Xiang independence movement|zh|\u6e56\u5357\u7701\u72ec\u7acb\u8fd0\u52a8}}\n|-\n|'''[[File:Proposed Yi flag.svg|23px|border]] Yi'''||\n|[[Xichang]]\n| align=\"center\" |60,261 || align=\"center\" |9,000,000 ||[[Yi people]]||Yi independence movement\n|-\n|'''[[File:Flag of Yuyencia.png|23px|border]] Yuyen'''||[[Beijing]]<br>[[Tianjin]]<br>[[Hebei]]<br>[[Liaoning]]<br>\n* [[Chaoyang, Liaoning|Chaoyang]]\n* [[Huludao]]\n[[Inner Mongolia]]<br>\n* [[Chifeng]]\n|[[Beijing]] (Yenching)\n| align=\"center\" |333,291 || align=\"center\" |118,000,000 ||Yuyen people||Yuyen independence movement\n|}\n\n== Taiwan (ROC) ==\n=== Overview of Taiwan (ROC) ===\n[[Image:Locator map of the ROC Taiwan.svg|thumb|right|ROC-controlled territories]]\n{{Main|Taiwan}}\n[[Taiwan|Taiwan (ROC)]] is a [[List of states with limited recognition|state with limited recognition]] located primarily on [[Geography of Taiwan|the main island of Taiwan]], as well as some satellite islands surrounding Taiwan, including the archipelagos of [[Penghu]], [[Kinmen]], and [[Matsu Islands|Matsu]]. The political status of Kinmen and Matsu within Taiwan is disputed.\n\nTaiwan (ROC) was preceded by two [[State (polity)|states]] which have, essentially, been in the process of merging into a single state since 1945.\n\n* [[Taiwan under Japanese rule|Japanese Formosa (Taiwan)]] \u2014 This state was a [[colony]] of the [[Empire of Japan|Japanese Empire]] for fifty years. The Japanese Empire had acquired the territory of Taiwan from the [[Qing dynasty]] (of China) after winning the [[First Sino-Japanese War]] in 1895. Due to the fact that Japanese Formosa previously belonged to a Chinese [[regime]], future Chinese regimes would all lay claim to Japanese Formosa after winning the [[Second Sino-Japanese War]].\n* [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)]] \u2014 This state once represented [[China and the United Nations|China in the United Nations]]. However, in 1949, the state lost the [[Chinese Civil War]] against the [[Communist Party of China|Chinese Communist Party]] and was forced to flee from its own borders and into Japanese Formosa. The Republic of China had recently occupied and annexed Japanese Formosa four years earlier, in 1945. This left a unique situation wherein the [[Rump state|rump-state]] of the Republic of China was, essentially, overlapping with the remnants of a now-defunct Japanese Formosa. Note that this was not a perfect overlap since the Republic of China still managed to hold onto a few small pieces of China, namely Kinmen (including [[Wuqiu, Kinmen|Wuqiu]]) and Matsu.\n\nIn modern times, the [[political status of Taiwan]] has developed into, perhaps, one of the most unique geopolitical anomalies currently in existence worldwide. The [[Revolution|revolutionary]] forces that drove the [[Republic of China on Taiwan|Republic of China out of China and into Taiwan]] established a new Chinese regime shortly before this occurred, and named it the \"[[China|People's Republic of China]]\". This regime not only lays claim to all of the Republic of China's previously-held territory in China but also the Republic of China's newly-acquired territory in Taiwan. To this day, the People's Republic of China is still laying claim to Taiwan, and the Republic of China still controls Taiwan.\n\n=== Ethnic groups of Taiwan (ROC) ===\n{{Main|Taiwanese people|Han Taiwanese|Taiwanese indigenous peoples}}\n[[Image:Map of Taiwan.jpg|thumb|right|Topography of Taiwan]]\n\nOfficially, Taiwan (ROC) is home to two main native ethnic groups, the [[Han Chinese]] (aka \"[[Han Taiwanese]]\") and the [[Taiwanese indigenous peoples]] (who are ethnically [[Austronesian peoples|Austronesian]]). Additionally, these two main native ethnic groups can be classified into several subdivisions. Regarding the Han Chinese, they can be divided into the [[Hoklo Taiwanese|Taiwanese Hoklo people]], the [[Taiwanese Hakka|Taiwanese Hakka people]], and the somewhat outdated term \"[[Mainland Chinese]] in Taiwan (ROC)\" (which refers to Mainland Chinese people who migrated to the territory of Taiwan during the late-1940s and early-1950s). Regarding the Taiwanese indigenous peoples, there are currently sixteen officially recognized tribes, and perhaps several more which are officially unrecognized. \n\nThe Taiwanese Hoklo and Taiwanese Hakka peoples, as well as, occasionally, the Taiwanese indigenous peoples, are often collectively referred to as \"Taiwanese Benshengren\" by the peoples of Taiwan (ROC), which roughly translates to \"Original Province Person(s)\". Meanwhile, the Mainland Chinese in Taiwan (ROC) (not to be confused with [[Chinese people|PRC citizens]] in Taiwan), who originate from various provinces of China, are often referred to as \"Taiwanese Waishengren\" by the peoples of Taiwan (ROC), which roughly translates to \"Outside Province Person(s)\".\n\nThese are the respective proportionate populations of these ethnic groups in Taiwan (ROC).\n\n* Taiwanese Benshengren people make up around 86% of the native population of Taiwan (ROC).\n** Taiwanese Hoklo people make up around 70% of the native population of Taiwan (ROC).\n** Taiwanese Hakka people make up around 14% of the native population of Taiwan (ROC).\n** Taiwanese indigenous peoples make up around 2% of the native population of Taiwan (ROC).\n* Taiwanese Waishengren people make up around 14% of the native population of Taiwan (ROC).\n\n==== The peoples of Kinmen (Quemoy) and Matsu (Lienchiang) ====\n{{See also|Taiwan independence movement#The issue of Kinmen (Quemoy) and Matsu (Lienchiang)}}\nFurthermore, the peoples of Kinmen and Matsu may identify themselves as \"Kinmenese\" and \"Matsunese\", respectively. The Kinmenese and Matsunese peoples are mostly Hoklo (Han) people, but whether they identify as \"Taiwanese\" is inconsistent throughout their populations. Historically, Kinmen and Matsu were parts of [[Fujian|Fujian Province, China]], and were never parts of Japanese Formosa or other historical Taiwanese regimes. However, Kinmen and Matsu have been administered by Taiwan (ROC) ever since 1949 (and by the ROC since it ruled mainland China). As such, although Kinmen and Matsu are not technically parts of the territory of Taiwan, many people living in these territories or originating from them view themselves as \"Taiwanese\", in a variety of contexts. Conversely, many people living in these territories still identify as Mainland Chinese, distinct from \"Mainland Chinese in Taiwan (ROC)\" or \"Taiwanese Waishengren\".\n\n==== Ethnic groups of Taiwan Province, PRC ====\n{{See also|Taiwan Province, People's Republic of China}}\nChina (PRC) claims [[Geography of Taiwan|Taiwan]] and [[Penghu]] as its own province and hence has its own ethnic classifications for the native ethnic groups. However, most countries disregard these ethnic classifications in favour of the local ethnic classifications defined by Taiwan (ROC).\n\nAccording to China (PRC), Taiwan is divided into the Han Chinese and the Gaoshanren. \"Gaoshanren\" means \"High mountain person(s)\" and refers to the various Taiwanese indigenous peoples as a single ethnic group.\n\n=== Primary forces supporting Taiwan independence ===\n{{Main|Taiwan independence movement|Pan-Green Coalition}}\n\n==== Pan-Green Coalition support for Taiwan independence ====\n[[Taiwan independence movement|Taiwan independence]] is a complex movement with many different parties being involved. The party which is most commonly associated with the movement is the [[Pan-Green Coalition]], a collective of several [[Political party|political parties]] which advocate for the independence of a [[Multiculturalism|multicultural]] [[sovereign state]] on Taiwan and [[Penghu]] (and sometimes also the ROC-controlled territories of [[Kinmen]] and [[Matsu Islands|Matsu]]) by the name of the \"Republic of Taiwan\". [[File:Flag of World Taiwanese Congress.svg|22px|border]] [[File:Flag of Taiwan proposed 1996.svg|22px|border]] [[File:908\u53f0\u7063\u570b\u904b\u52d5.svg|22px|border]] This movement is the most well-known one internationally since the most senior political party in the Pan-Green Coalition, the [[Democratic Progressive Party]], has risen to power in Taiwan (ROC) twice within the past two decades. Notably, this has been achieved by [[Democracy|democratic]] [[Election|elections]], rather than by [[Coup d'\u00e9tat|military coup]]. This indicates that there is widespread support (or, at the very least, complacency) in Taiwan (ROC) regarding the Taiwan independence movement (as defined by the Pan-Green Coalition).\n\nOther major political parties associated with the Pan-Green Coalition include the [[New Power Party]] and the [[Taiwan Solidarity Union]]. Additionally the organization [[World United Formosans for Independence]] is an ally of the Pan-Green Coalition.\n\n==== Indigenous independence movements ====\n\nWhile many [[Taiwanese aborigines|Taiwanese indigenous people(s)]] support the Pan-Green Coalition, many also support the [[Taiwan First Nations Party]], a political party in Taiwan (ROC) which specifically advocates for the autonomy or possible independence of the Taiwan indigenous peoples. The [[Council of Indigenous Peoples]] is also closely affiliated with the movement advocating for Taiwanese indigenous autonomy or independence. An autonomous or independent Taiwanese indigenous state might be named \"[[Taiwanese indigenous peoples#Aboriginal political movement|Aborigines of Taiwan's Autonomy]]\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.culturalsurvival.org/publications/cultural-survival-quarterly/first-nations-taiwan-special-report-taiwans-indigenous|title=The First Nations of Taiwan: A Special Report on Taiwan's indigenous peoples|website=www.culturalsurvival.org|language=en|access-date=2019-01-30}}</ref>.\n\n=== Primary forces opposed to Taiwan independence ===\n{{Main|One-China policy|Anti-Secession Law|1992 Consensus}}\nThe relationship of China with Taiwan is confusing and convoluted. Simply put, Taiwan (ROC) is an independent country which is competing with China (PRC) for recognition as the sole legitimate government of China, and within Taiwan (ROC) there is a nationwide secessionist movement which has garnered the support of roughly half the country. The secessionist movement in Taiwan (ROC) is equally aimed at both the Taiwan (ROC) government itself as well as the China (PRC) government which is claiming the entirety of Taiwan (ROC) as its own territory.\n\nChina (PRC) is widely recognized as the legitimate government of both China and Taiwan. This means that the Taiwan (ROC) country is not only fighting against Taiwanese secessionists, but also against China (PRC) simultaneously. Compared to China (PRC), Taiwan (ROC) is at a severe disadvantage but isn't completely powerless, since most of the world isn't too supportive of the possible dissolving of the Taiwan (ROC) country. However, the sovereignty of Taiwan (ROC) is being critically threatened by the Taiwan independence movement, which essentially aims to overthrow Taiwan (ROC).\n\n==== China (PRC) opposition to Taiwan independence ====\n{{Main|Taiwan, China}}\nChina (PRC) considers Taiwan area, which is currently administered by Taiwan (ROC), as part of its own territory, and forces other countries to abide by a \"[[One-China policy]]\" as a prerequisite for establishing official diplomatic relations with China (PRC). The One-China policy is aimed at both the rival Chinese government known as the \"Republic of China\", as well as the localist Taiwan independence movement. In 2005, China (PRC) passed the \"[[Anti-Secession Law]]\" in an attempt to suppress the Taiwan independence movement.\n\n==== Pan-Blue Coalition opposition to Taiwan independence ====\n{{Main|Pan-Blue Coalition}}\nThe [[Pan-Blue Coalition]] of Taiwan (ROC) is an alliance of political parties which are loyal to the ROC, currently restricted to the territory of Taiwan and some minor islands of Fujian Province. The Pan-Blue Coalition asserts that the ROC is the sole legitimate government of all of China, which consists of \"both mainland China and Taiwan\", and that the ROC has never for a single day lost its sovereignty. The Pan-Blue Coalition is opposed to Taiwan independence but is also opposed to a PRC takeover of Taiwan.\n\n== China (PRC) (aka \"mainland China\") ==\n[[File:China autonomous regions numbered.svg|thumb]]\n\n\n{{further|Autonomous administrative divisions of China|Special administrative regions of China|One country, Two systems||}}\n\nThe [[People's Republic of China|People's Republic of China (China/PRC)]] considers itself to be the sole legitimate government of \"both mainland China area and Taiwan area\".\n\nThe territory controlled by the PRC consists of [[mainland China]], [[Hong Kong]], and [[Macau]]. The PRC also claims all [[Taiwan|ROC]]-controlled territories as part of its own territory. The PRC has established \"[[Special administrative regions of China|Special Administrative Regions]]\" (SARs) in [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macau]] under the [[one country, two systems|One Country Two Systems]] policy. \n\n=== Tibet region (Qinghai, Xizang, etc) ===\n{{Main|Tibetan independence movement}}\n\nThe [[Tibetan people|Tibetans]] are an ethnic group in Tibet that is distinct from the [[Han Chinese]]. Their proposed state is Tibet. {{flagicon|Tibet}} Supporters of Tibetan independence believe that Tibet is a distinct country which is being occupied by China (PRC). The [[Tibet|Tibet region]] was independent before the [[Mongols]] invaded the Tibet region and incorporated it into the [[Mongol Empire]]. After this, Tibet became part of the [[Yuan dynasty]] (of China), then the [[Qing dynasty]] (of China), then experienced a few decades of ''de facto'' independence before it was incorporated into China (PRC). \n\nAfter the failed Tibetan uprising, some Tibetans followed the Dalai Lama into India, establishing a government-in-exile called the [[Central Tibetan Administration]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dalailama.com/page.99.htm|title=Speech of His Holiness the Dalai Lama to the European Parliament, Strasbourg|date=14 October 2001|publisher=The Office of His Holiness the Dalai Lama|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325221348/http://www.dalailama.com/page.99.htm|archivedate=25 March 2009|url-status=dead|accessdate=11 April 2009}}</ref>, a member of the [[Unrepresented Nations and Peoples Organization]], in Dharmashala, Himachal Pradesh, India. The major political parties in Tibet are the [[International Tibet Independence Movement]] and the [[National Democratic Party of Tibet]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rangzen.org/|title=INTERNATIONAL TIBET INDEPENDENCE MOVEMENT|publisher=International Tibet Independence Movement|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416141657/http://www.rangzen.org/|archive-date=16 April 2009|url-status=live|accessdate=11 April 2009}}</ref>. Their advocacy groups include the [[Students for a Free Tibet]], the [[Tibetan Youth Congress]], and the [[International Campaign for Tibet]].\n\n=== Xinjiang Autonomous Region ===\n{{Main|Uyghur independence}}\nXinjiang is home to several ethnic groups, including the [[Uyghurs]], the [[Kazakhs in China|Kazakhs]], the [[Tajiks of Xinjiang|Tajiks]], as well as the [[Han Chinese]]. \n\nThe ethnic Uyghur people view themselves as [[Indigenous peoples|indigenous]] to Xinjiang, but the government of China (PRC) opposes this notion. Whether they are indigenous is very significant, because it defines whether Xinjiang \"belongs\" to the Uyghurs or to China (PRC). China (PRC) has been in the process of encouraging Han Chinese settlement in Xinjiang for several decades, which is a source of concern for the Uyghur secessionists of Xinjiang.\n\nThe Uyghur secessionists propose independence for Xinjiang as [[East Turkestan]]. [[File:Kokbayraq flag.svg|22px|border]] The borders of the proposed state will roughly match the borders of the Chinese autonomous region which currently occupies the territory. Uyghur secessionists have set up a government-in-exile called the [[East Turkistan Government in Exile|East Turkestan Government in Exile]]. \n\nThe main advocacy group of Uyghur independence is the [[World Uyghur Congress]], a member of the [[Unrepresented Nations and Peoples Organization]].\n\n==== Conflict in Xinjiang ====\n{{Main|Xinjiang conflict|Xinjiang re-education camps}}\nSeveral armed insurgency groups are fighting the Chinese (PRC) government in Xinjiang, namely the [[Turkistan Islamic Party|Turkestan Islamic Party]] and the [[East Turkestan Liberation Organization]], which some people consider to be associated with [[Al Qaeda|Al-Qaeda]] and the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thediplomat.com/2017/03/al-qaeda-and-islamic-state-take-aim-at-china/|title=Al-Qaeda and Islamic State Take Aim at China. Why have both groups turned their attention to Beijing?|website=The Diplomat|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314072328/http://thediplomat.com/2017/03/al-qaeda-and-islamic-state-take-aim-at-china/|archive-date=14 March 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref>.\n\nIn response, China (PRC) has established so-called \"re-education camps\" in Xinjiang, allegedly as a measure to deal with this violent insurgency, which China (PRC) has labelled as \"terrorism\".\n\nThese re-education camps have become a huge source of controversy in the [[Western world|West]], due to concerns that they are imprisoning ethnic Uyghurs and other [[Islam in China|native Muslims]] ''en masse'' without trial.\n\nChina (PRC) claims that the World Uyghur Congress is formally associated with terrorist groups in Xinjiang, but this has yet to be proven.\n\n=== Inner Mongolia ===\n{{Main|Inner Mongolian independence movement}}\n\nThe region of [[Inner Mongolia]] is home to several ethnic groups, namely the Han Chinese and [[Mongolian people|Mongolians]].\n\nSome Mongolians in Inner Mongolia advocate for the independence of Inner Mongolia as a new country named [[Inner Mongolian People's Party|Republic of South Mongolia]] [[File:Flag of the Inner Mongolian People's Party.svg|22px|border]] or unification with [[Mongolia|Mongolia.]] {{flagicon|Mongolia}} \n\nSouth Mongolian independence is supported by these political parties: the [[Inner Mongolian People's Party]], a member of the [[Unrepresented Nations and Peoples Organization]]; the [[Southern Mongolian Democratic Alliance]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smhric.org/news_39.htm|title=\"Inner Mongolian People's Party\" and the basic facts about its key members|publisher=Southern Mongolian Human Rights Information Center|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225210314/http://www.smhric.org/news_39.htm|archive-date=25 February 2009|url-status=live|accessdate=11 April 2009}}</ref>; and the [[Mongolian Liberal Union Party]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lupm.org/japanese/index.htm|title=\u30e2\u30f3\u30b4\u30eb\u81ea\u7531\u9023\u76df\u515a|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100726004625/http://www.lupm.org/japanese/index.htm|archive-date=26 July 2010|url-status=live|accessdate=22 November 2010}}(JP)</ref>.\n\n==Special Administrative Regions of China==\n[[Image:China Hong Kong location map.svg|frameless|right]]\n=== Hong Kong ===\n{{Main|Hong Kong}}\n\n==== Background ====\n{{Main|History of Hong Kong}}\n'''[[Hong Kong]]''' is a highly [[Autonomous administrative division|autonomous]] [[city]] that is under Chinese sovereignty but operates as an independent country in many respects and is somewhat comparable to a [[Dependent territory|dependency]]. Officially, Hong Kong is considered to be a [[Special administrative regions of China|'''Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China''']]. Geographically, Hong Kong is attached to [[mainland China]] via [[Guangdong|Guangdong Province]] in the [[South China|south]] but lies mostly on a small [[peninsula]], of which [[Kowloon Peninsula]] is a part, as well as many small islands nearby to the peninsula, the most notable of which is [[Hong Kong Island]].\n\nHistorically, Hong Kong Island was ceded by the [[Qing dynasty]] to the [[British Empire]] in 1842 following the British victory in the [[First Opium War]] and was promptly developed into a [[Crown colony|British colony]]. The nearby Kowloon Peninsula was ceded in 1860 following the British victory in the [[Second Opium War]] and was incorporated into Hong Kong. Finally, the last major territorial acquisition was the nearby [[New Territories]], leased by the British for 99 years in 1898 by means of the [[Convention for the Extension of Hong Kong Territory]]; this territorial change was made in the aftermath of the [[First Sino-Japanese War]], which Hong Kong was not directly involved in.\n\nIn 1997, the [[China|People's Republic of China]] and the [[United Kingdom|United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland]] signed the [[Sino-British Joint Declaration]] in order to [[Handover of Hong Kong|transfer Hong Kong]] from the United Kingdom to China. China agreed to govern Hong Kong under a so-called \"[[One country, two systems|One Country Two Systems]]\" framework, which would grant Hong Kong a high degree of autonomy whilst simultaneously granting China sovereignty over Hong Kong.\n\n==== Culture ====\n{{Main|Culture of Hong Kong}}\nThe three main regions of Hong Kong, consisting of Hong Kong Island, Kowloon Peninsula, and the New Territories, were all under British rule for different lengths of time, ranging from 99 to 155 years. Due to this lengthy period of British rule, Hong Kong's infrastructure, society, and culture became broadly British. Hong Kong also developed a distinct culture from mainland China because many [[Mainland Chinese]] immigrated to Hong Kong, often illegally, in order to escape persecution by the [[Communist Party of China]] or to seek better living standards. Most of the Mainland Chinese immigrants to Hong Kong were [[Cantonese people]], though there were also significant numbers of [[Hoklo people|Hoklo]], [[Teochew people|Teochew]], [[Hakka people|Hakka]], and [[Shanghainese people|Shanghainese]] immigrants. In the present day, the vast majority of Hong Kong people can trace their ancestry, whether fully or partially, to these Cantonese immigrants or others who came to Hong Kong throughout the 20th century. Native Hong Kong people, that is, people who were living in Hong Kong prior to British rule, constitute a minority of the population. Hong Kong also hosts minority populations of [[South Asian ethnic groups|South Asians]], [[Ethnic groups of Southeast Asia|Southeast Asians]], [[Ethnic groups in Europe|Europeans]], [[North America|North Americans]], and other broad ethnic groups.\n\n==== Independence movement ====\n{{main|Hong Kong independence}}The Hong Kong independence movement advocates for the full independence of Hong Kong as a \"[[city-state]]\", similar to [[Singapore]]. Related sovereign movements in Hong Kong include the movement to maintain Hong Kong's status as a \"Special Administrative Region\" indefinitely, the movement to return Hong Kong to [[British Hong Kong|British rule]], the movement to admit Hong Kong into the [[United States|United States of America]], and the movement to admit Hong Kong into the [[Taiwan|Republic of China (Taiwan)]].\n\n=== Macau ===\n{{Empty section|date=January 2020}}\n\n==Related pages==\n* [[Demographics of China#Population density and distribution|Demographics of China]]\n* [[Template:Han Chinese subgroups]]\n* [[Ethnic minorities in China]]\n* [[Ethnic issues in China]]\n* [[Ethnic groups in Chinese history]]\n* [[Languages of China]]\n* [[Language Atlas of China]]\n* [[Standard Chinese]]\n* [[Autonomous administrative divisions of China]]\n* [[Administrative divisions of China]]\n* [[Autonomous regions of China]]\n* [[Anti-Secession Law]]\n* [[Xinjiang conflict]]\n* [[List of active separatist movements in Asia]]\n* [[Political status of Taiwan]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Other websites==\n* {{YouTube|C4W5Rhg9wIk|China must stop the genocide in East Turkestan Special News Daily Voice News}}\n\n{{Secession in Countries}}\n\n[[Category:National liberation movements]]\n[[Category:Politics of China]]\n[[Category:Separatism in China]]\n", "name_user": "36.225.156.73", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eList of secessionist movements in People's Republic of China)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secession_in_China"}
{"title_page": "Harriet Creighton", "text_new": "'''Harriet Baldwin Creighton''' (27 June 1909 &ndash; January 9, 2004) was an [[United States|American]] [[botanist]], [[geneticist]] and educator.\n\n==Background==\nBorn in [[Delavan, Illinois|Delavan]], [[Illinois]], Creighton graduated from [[Wellesley College]] in 1929, and went on to complete her Ph.D. at [[Cornell University]] in 1933.\n\n==Career==\nDuring her time at Cornell she worked in the field of maize [[cytogenetics]] with [[Barbara McClintock]], the pair published a very influential paper in 1931 in which they described [[chromosomal crossover]] for the first time. This paper, part of her Ph.D. research, provided key evidence that chromosomes carried and exchanged genetic information and hence that genes for physical traits are carried on chromosomes. Barbara McClintock guided her Ph.D. research.<ref>Kass, Lee B.  2005c.  Harriet Creighton: Proud botanist.  Plant Science Bulletin.  51(4): 118-125.  Available online, December 2005: http://www.botany.org/PlantScienceBulletin/PSB-2005-51-4.php#HARRIET {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004012334/http://www.botany.org/plantsciencebulletin/psb-2005-51-4.php |date=2013-10-04 }}; Kass, L. B. and Chomet, P. 2009.  Barbara McClintock, Pgs.  17-52, in J. Bennetzen and S. Hake, Editors, Handbook of Maize: Genetics and Genomics. Springer</ref>\n\nAfter completing her Ph.D. she taught at [[Cornell University]] and [[Connecticut College]], and then returned to [[Wellesley College]] where she taught until her retirement in 1974; taking time from her career to serve in the [[U.S. Navy]] during [[World War II]].<ref>Kass, Lee B.  2005c.  Harriet Creighton: Proud botanist.  Plant Science Bulletin.  51(4): 118-125.  Available online, December 2005: http://www.botany.org/PlantScienceBulletin/PSB-2005-51-4.php#HARRIET {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004012334/http://www.botany.org/plantsciencebulletin/psb-2005-51-4.php |date=2013-10-04 }}; Kass, Lee B. 2007a. Harriet B. Creighton (1909-2004), on Women Pioneers in Plant Biology, American Society of Plant Biologists website, Ann Hirsch editor. Published online, February 2007: http://www.aspb.org/committees/women/pioneers.cfm#Creighton {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031203235101/http://www.aspb.org/committees/women/pioneers.cfm |date=2003-12-03 }}; Kass, Lee B. 2007b. Barbara McClintock (1902-1992), on Women Pioneers in Plant Biology, American Society of Plant Biologists website, Ann Hirsch editor. Published online, March 2007: http://www.aspb.org/committees/women/pioneers.cfm#McClintock</ref>\n\n'''Key Publication'''\n\n{{cite journal | pmid = 16587654 | pmc=1076098 | volume=17 | title=A Correlation of Cytological and Genetical Crossing-Over in Zea Mays | date=August 1931 | journal=Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | pages=492\u20137  | last1 = Creighton | first1 = HB | last2 = McClintock | first2 = B}}.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.wellesley.edu/PublicAffairs/Wwire/2004/012904.html#two ''Wellesley Wire'': \"Harriet Creighton, long-time professor of botany, dies\" (January 29, 2004)];\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Kass | first1 = Lee | year = 2005 | title = Harriet B. Creighton: Proud Botanist | url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131004012334/http://www.botany.org/plantsciencebulletin/psb-2005-51-4.php#HARRIET | journal = Plant Science Bulletin | volume = 51 | issue = 4| pages = 118\u2013125 }}\n**Kass, Lee B.  2005c, ''Plant Science Bulletin'':  \"Harriet B. Creighton: Proud botanist\" 51(4): 118\u2013125.  Available online, December 2005: https://web.archive.org/web/20131004012334/http://www.botany.org/plantsciencebulletin/psb-2005-51-4.php#HARRIET\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20031203235101/http://www.aspb.org/committees/women/pioneers.cfm#Creighton Kass, Lee B. 2007a. \"Women Pioneers in Plant Biology\" - Barbara McClintock (1902-1992)\"] \u2014 American Society of Plant Biologists website, An